      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Property with a Caveat in Brisbane: What Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A caveat on your title does not prevent you from selling, but it does need to be resolved before settlement. Here is how caveats work in Queensland and what sellers should do.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Finding a caveat on your title when you are preparing to sell can be alarming, particularly if you were not aware it had been lodged. In most cases it is a resolvable problem, but it does add complexity to the sale process and needs to be handled correctly. Understanding what a caveat is, why it has been lodged, and what options exist for removing it will help you work with your solicitor to manage the issue without derailing your campaign or settlement timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a caveat is</h2>
      <p>A caveat is a formal notice lodged on a property's title through the Queensland Titles Registry that records a third party's claim to an interest in the property. The word comes from the Latin for "let him beware," and in property law it functions as a warning to anyone dealing with the property that another party has a claimed interest that must be resolved before the property can be dealt with freely.</p>

      <p>A caveat does not transfer ownership and it does not prevent the property from being sold. What it does is alert the buyer and their solicitor that a third party is asserting a legal or equitable interest, which means the property cannot change hands with clean title until that interest is dealt with. In practice, this almost always means the caveat must be removed before settlement proceeds.</p>

      <p>Caveats can only be lodged by someone who genuinely believes they have a legal or equitable interest in the property. Lodging a caveat without a proper basis is a serious matter under Queensland law and can expose the caveator to a claim for compensation if the caveat causes the owner loss.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common reasons caveats are lodged</h2>
      <p>Unpaid debts are among the most common triggers. A tradesperson, contractor, or lender who is owed money and believes they have a security interest in the property may lodge a caveat to protect their position while a debt is being disputed or recovered. This is more common with properties that have been renovated recently or that have a private loan or second mortgage arrangement in place.</p>

      <p>Family law and relationship property disputes frequently produce caveats. When a relationship breaks down and one party believes they have a claim to the property held in the other party's name, lodging a caveat preserves their position while legal proceedings are under way. These caveats can be particularly complex to resolve quickly, as they often require either a negotiated agreement or court intervention.</p>

      <p>Equitable interests arising from informal arrangements are another source. If someone has contributed to the purchase price or improvement of a property without being recorded on the title, they may lodge a caveat to protect a constructive or resulting trust claim. These arrangements are more common in family or de facto property situations.</p>

      <p>Trust arrangements, company structures, and estate matters can also produce caveats. A beneficiary under a trust or estate who believes the trustee is dealing with trust property incorrectly may lodge a caveat to prevent a transaction proceeding without resolution of the trust dispute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Whether you can sell with a caveat in place</h2>
      <p>Listing the property and accepting an offer with a caveat on the title is generally possible. The caveat does not prevent the formation of a contract. What it does prevent is the completion of settlement and the passing of clean title to a buyer, which is what the buyer is paying for. This means that even if you have an executed contract, you cannot settle until the caveat is resolved.</p>

      <p>If the caveat cannot be resolved within the settlement period, the buyer may have grounds to delay or terminate the contract depending on the specific contract terms and the nature of the caveat. Queensland standard contracts include provisions that allow buyers to raise title defects as requisitions, and a caveat is typically treated as a title defect requiring the seller's response and resolution.</p>

      <p>For sellers who discover a caveat during the campaign, it is important not to conceal it. Your solicitor will be managing the title, and the caveat will appear in any title search the buyer conducts. Attempting to proceed without disclosing a known caveat exposes you to legal risk and can give the buyer grounds to terminate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How caveats affect the sale timeline</h2>
      <p>The impact on your timeline depends on how quickly the caveat can be resolved. A voluntary withdrawal by the caveator, which happens when the underlying dispute or debt is settled directly, can be arranged in days. A formal lapsing notice process takes a minimum of 14 days and requires the Titles Registry to serve notice on the caveator, who then has that period to apply to the Supreme Court for an extension. If the caveator does not apply within 14 days, the caveat lapses automatically.</p>

      <p>If the matter goes to the Supreme Court, whether because the caveator applies to extend or because the seller seeks a court order for removal, the timeline extends significantly and legal costs increase materially. This scenario is most common in family law or trust disputes where the underlying claim is genuinely contested.</p>

      <p>Sellers who know about a caveat before launching their campaign are in the best position to resolve it without affecting the sale. Engaging a solicitor to address the caveat before listing means the title will be clear by the time a buyer conducts their searches, and the campaign can proceed without complications.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The removal process in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor has three primary pathways for caveat removal. The first and fastest is voluntary withdrawal. If you can resolve the underlying issue with the caveator directly, whether by paying a disputed debt, reaching a settlement on a family law claim, or clarifying a misunderstanding about an interest in the property, the caveator can lodge a withdrawal of caveat form with the Titles Registry and the caveat is removed, usually within a few business days.</p>

      <p>The second pathway is a lapsing notice. The registered owner (you, as the seller) can serve a notice on the caveator through the Titles Registry requiring them to either withdraw the caveat or apply to the Supreme Court to extend it within 14 days. If the caveator takes no action, the caveat lapses automatically after the notice period. This is a useful mechanism when the caveator's claim is weak or they are simply unresponsive, but it requires a solicitor to manage the process correctly.</p>

      <p>The third pathway is a court order for removal. This is used when the caveator refuses to withdraw, the lapsing process has been contested, or the situation requires judicial determination of the underlying claim. Court proceedings take months rather than days and involve significant legal costs. Sellers should understand this risk if their caveat situation is contested.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers do when they find a caveat</h2>
      <p>A caveat appears on a standard title search, which the buyer's solicitor conducts as part of routine due diligence. When a caveat is identified, the buyer's solicitor will raise it as a requisition on title, formally requiring the seller to respond with evidence that the caveat will be removed before settlement.</p>

      <p>An experienced buyer's solicitor will also consider the nature of the caveat and the likelihood of timely resolution when advising their client about whether to proceed, request a delayed settlement date, or seek additional security that the caveat will be resolved. A caveat with a clear resolution path, backed by a letter from a solicitor confirming the withdrawal is in progress, is generally less concerning to a buyer than one where the nature and timeline of resolution is unclear.</p>

      <p>Buyers are not entitled to terminate a Queensland standard contract simply because a caveat exists, unless the seller has failed to respond to a requisition or the caveat genuinely prevents settlement from occurring within the contract timeframe. Sellers who handle the disclosure and resolution process transparently, with their solicitor communicating proactively with the buyer's solicitor, typically manage caveat situations without losing buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Working with your solicitor</h2>
      <p>Caveat situations require legal advice specific to the circumstances. The appropriate resolution pathway, the correct process for serving notices, and the assessment of whether the caveator's claimed interest has any legal merit are all matters that require a Queensland property solicitor, not general guidance. Your conveyancer or solicitor should be engaged as early as possible once a caveat is identified, preferably before you list the property if you are already aware of the issue.</p>

      <p>A solicitor who practises Queensland property law regularly will have dealt with caveat situations before and will be able to advise you quickly on the likely resolution timeline and cost. That information allows you and your agent to plan the campaign and settlement timeline around the caveat process, rather than discovering the problem mid-campaign when a buyer is waiting.</p>

